WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.437 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.437 --> 00:00:09.367 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:09.367 --> 00:00:28.241 align:middle line:90%


00:00:28.241 --> 00:00:30.490 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: As much
as we try to tell ourselves

00:00:30.490 --> 00:00:33.330 align:middle line:10%
that we as women are liberated
from the chains of servitude

00:00:33.330 --> 00:00:35.530 align:middle line:10%
of the past, we
often remain slaves

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:37.490 align:middle line:10%
to our own minds and DNA.

00:00:37.490 --> 00:00:39.800 align:middle line:84%
You can't take thousands
of years of programming

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.760 align:middle line:84%
of being perceived
as lesser than

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:44.090 align:middle line:84%
and have that healed in
four to five decades.

00:00:44.090 --> 00:00:46.130 align:middle line:90%
But it is beginning to heal.

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:48.660 align:middle line:84%
Cate Montana, author
of "Unearthing Venus,"

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:51.960 align:middle line:84%
tells her version of the story
of what it is to be a woman.

00:00:51.960 --> 00:00:55.160 align:middle line:84%
A very courageous memoir,
Cate shares the fear and hope

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:57.700 align:middle line:84%
of women everywhere
that the time truly

00:00:57.700 --> 00:00:59.310 align:middle line:84%
comes when we can
be seen for who

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:02.570 align:middle line:84%
we are among men but
also among ourselves.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:03.680 align:middle line:90%
Cate, what a book.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:04.890 align:middle line:90%
Whoa.

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:07.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm sure
every woman and-- do

00:01:07.470 --> 00:01:08.870 align:middle line:90%
men read your book, as well?

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:10.620 align:middle line:84%
>>CATE MONTANA: I've been really
surprised at how many men.

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:12.090 align:middle line:90%
It's actually about 50-50.

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:13.173 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's fabulous.

00:01:13.173 --> 00:01:16.610 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: And a positive,
very enthusiastic response

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:17.520 align:middle line:90%
from both sexes.

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:22.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well this is one of
the most vulnerable, revealing

00:01:22.270 --> 00:01:27.120 align:middle line:84%
memoirs on what it is to be a
woman that I have ever read.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:32.140 align:middle line:84%
And, you know, it's like you--
this conversation will reveal

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:34.090 align:middle line:84%
it-- we've been down a
lot of the same roads.

00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:34.710 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Yeah, we have.

00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:36.390 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And the
whole road of feminism

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:39.170 align:middle line:84%
is not anything that
has ever interested me.

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:41.340 align:middle line:84%
But as you go through
life, you start

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:43.980 align:middle line:84%
seeing these
essential areas that

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:47.030 align:middle line:84%
just have to be mended
up, where the wounds are,

00:01:47.030 --> 00:01:48.110 align:middle line:90%
between the sexes.

00:01:48.110 --> 00:01:49.422 align:middle line:90%
And it has to be talked about.

00:01:49.422 --> 00:01:50.130 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Right.

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:52.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So first of all,
you start your book out,

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:54.300 align:middle line:84%
I think, at a very
appropriate place,

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:55.900 align:middle line:84%
which I'd like you
to share with us,

00:01:55.900 --> 00:01:58.560 align:middle line:84%
with one of my favorite
interviewees-- John Perkins.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:01:59.800 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: John Perkins.

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:02.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And work
with the Shuar tribe

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:05.850 align:middle line:84%
and talking about the difference
between men and women.

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:07.790 align:middle line:84%
And if you will, please,
set the stage for us

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:10.042 align:middle line:84%
and share that and share
why you shared that

00:02:10.042 --> 00:02:11.250 align:middle line:90%
at the beginning of the book.

00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:12.740 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: OK.

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:15.692 align:middle line:10%
And you're right,
the last thing I ever

00:02:15.692 --> 00:02:17.400 align:middle line:10%
thought that I would
ever get involved in

00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:19.790 align:middle line:10%
would be feminist
anything, that I would ever

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:22.960 align:middle line:10%
write about feminine
oriented anything,

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.516 align:middle line:10%
or even write an article
about the feminine.

00:02:25.516 --> 00:02:26.140 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.598 align:middle line:10%
>>MONTANA: So this book came
as a big surprise for me, too.

00:02:28.598 --> 00:02:30.840 align:middle line:10%
And John Perkins is
totally responsible.

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:35.220 align:middle line:84%
I was doing a article
and interview with him

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:36.906 align:middle line:84%
for an article for
"Indian Country

00:02:36.906 --> 00:02:40.010 align:middle line:84%
Today," a national
Native American paper.

00:02:40.010 --> 00:02:42.530 align:middle line:84%
I've been a newspaper
and magazine

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:45.430 align:middle line:90%
journalist for about 25 years.

00:02:45.430 --> 00:02:47.454 align:middle line:90%
And this was way back in 1999.

00:02:47.454 --> 00:02:49.870 align:middle line:84%
So we're in the middle of this
conversation and interview,

00:02:49.870 --> 00:02:51.750 align:middle line:84%
and he starts talking
about the Shuar tribe

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:57.680 align:middle line:84%
down in the Brazilian rainforest
and their gender differences

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:01.730 align:middle line:84%
and how they've segmented their
society along gender lines.

00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:03.390 align:middle line:90%
The men do guy things.

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:05.290 align:middle line:84%
They hunt and they
fish and they cut down

00:03:05.290 --> 00:03:07.420 align:middle line:90%
trees for the huts and canoes.

00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:08.970 align:middle line:84%
And the women do
domestic chores,

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:11.760 align:middle line:84%
take care of the children,
gather wild edibles.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:13.680 align:middle line:90%
Nothing new there.

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:17.670 align:middle line:84%
Both men and women are equally
represented on tribal council.

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:19.770 align:middle line:90%
That was-- OK.

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:22.170 align:middle line:84%
So there wasn't
any-- and there was

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:24.760 align:middle line:90%
no battle of the sexes going on.

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:28.090 align:middle line:84%
It was very clear when he talked
about their gender dynamics

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:31.440 align:middle line:84%
that men and women
understood themselves

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:34.270 align:middle line:84%
in a larger context
than just he and she,

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:36.390 align:middle line:84%
that they were actually
getting into a lot

00:03:36.390 --> 00:03:40.359 align:middle line:84%
of qualitative aspects of
being a man, being a woman.

00:03:40.359 --> 00:03:41.900 align:middle line:84%
They played to each
other's strengths

00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:43.490 align:middle line:90%
rather than their weaknesses.

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:47.660 align:middle line:84%
And he said that there
was one job, however,

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:50.520 align:middle line:84%
in this tribe that only
the women could do.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:53.200 align:middle line:84%
And that the survival of the
tribe depended upon the women

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:54.110 align:middle line:90%
doing this one job.

00:03:54.110 --> 00:03:56.443 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, the first
thing that went off in my mind

00:03:56.443 --> 00:03:58.865 align:middle line:90%
was right, have babies, biology.

00:03:58.865 --> 00:03:59.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Cook.

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:00.480 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Cook, yeah.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:02.820 align:middle line:84%
And he said, no,
that's not it at all.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:06.530 align:middle line:84%
He said the Shuar
tribe understands

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:10.570 align:middle line:84%
the masculine nature
tends towards being goal

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:15.510 align:middle line:84%
oriented, directed,
aggressive, competitive, pedal

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:16.089 align:middle line:90%
to the metal.

00:04:16.089 --> 00:04:17.005 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Destructive.

00:04:17.005 --> 00:04:20.910 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: As a result, pedal
to the metal, no stop button.

00:04:20.910 --> 00:04:21.649 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:23.950 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: They
understood woman's nature

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:29.950 align:middle line:84%
is much more intuitive, much
more community oriented, much

00:04:29.950 --> 00:04:32.360 align:middle line:84%
more grounded in
relationship, whether it

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:36.620 align:middle line:84%
was the needs of the tribe or
the needs of their relationship

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:37.360 align:middle line:90%
with the earth.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:41.520 align:middle line:84%
So the men absolutely depended
upon the women telling them

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:42.290 align:middle line:90%
when to stop.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:43.790 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that
was what I liked.

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:47.255 align:middle line:84%
He said the men will fish
until there are no more fish.

00:04:47.255 --> 00:04:47.880 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Yep.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:50.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They will
kill the animals

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.990 align:middle line:84%
until there are no more
animals and on and on.

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:56.250 align:middle line:84%
And it's up to the women
to tell us when to stop.

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:58.620 align:middle line:84%
And didn't he say then,
why aren't your women

00:04:58.620 --> 00:04:59.817 align:middle line:90%
telling you to stop?

00:04:59.817 --> 00:05:01.650 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: Well, the
first part of the story

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:03.060 align:middle line:90%
rocked my world, Regina.

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:06.270 align:middle line:84%
And then he followed
it up with that.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:08.210 align:middle line:84%
He asked me, he
said-- and this is

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:10.970 align:middle line:84%
what he was asked by this
shaman in the tribe--

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:13.430 align:middle line:84%
where are your
Western women today?

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:15.960 align:middle line:84%
Why are you not telling
your men to stop?

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:21.640 align:middle line:84%
You are taking the world over
a cliff, depleting resources.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:22.240 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:22.850 align:middle line:90%
Where are you?

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:23.370 align:middle line:90%
What are you doing?

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:24.495 align:middle line:90%
I'm like, oh, I don't know.

00:05:24.495 --> 00:05:27.220 align:middle line:84%
I'm out there busy making
a buck, making a living,

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:31.390 align:middle line:84%
being just as aggressive,
having not a clue where the stop

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:34.610 align:middle line:84%
button is probably
more than any man.

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:36.430 align:middle line:84%
Because I have more
to prove because I

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.550 align:middle line:84%
came on deck in the '60s
and '70s as a woman.

00:05:39.550 --> 00:05:40.537 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, we're--

00:05:40.537 --> 00:05:41.940 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: We'll get into that.

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:42.650 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We're going
to get into that.

00:05:42.650 --> 00:05:43.360 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Yeah.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:43.985 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:05:43.985 --> 00:05:45.390 align:middle line:90%
And so that's true.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:48.080 align:middle line:84%
Oftentimes the women possess
more of the masculine traits

00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:49.650 align:middle line:84%
when you feel as
though you've had

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:51.272 align:middle line:84%
to fight for your
place in the world.

00:05:51.272 --> 00:05:51.980 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Right.

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:55.640 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so this isn't--
doesn't have to do with body

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:57.392 align:middle line:90%
parts, as we said off camera.

00:05:57.392 --> 00:05:58.100 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Right.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.740 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: These
are deeper traits.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.360 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: That conversation
changed my entire life.

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:06.580 align:middle line:84%
I wrote the article and I was
still reeling weeks later,

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:11.650 align:middle line:84%
contemplating the power
that the Shuar women had

00:06:11.650 --> 00:06:15.350 align:middle line:84%
to be able to tell the men to
do anything, let alone stop.

00:06:15.350 --> 00:06:17.870 align:middle line:84%
Can you imagine the women when
everybody is coming across

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:20.840 align:middle line:84%
in the wagon trains and
the railroads to the West

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:22.620 align:middle line:84%
and they're out
blitzkrieging the buffalo

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:25.642 align:middle line:84%
by the hundreds of thousands
and just laying waste to them.

00:06:25.642 --> 00:06:27.974 align:middle line:84%
And women saying, I don't
think you should do that.

00:06:27.974 --> 00:06:29.265 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, right, exactly.

00:06:29.265 --> 00:06:32.430 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: Because we had
no real validity as women.

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:33.850 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't
until-- You know, I

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:35.190 align:middle line:90%
thought about it more and more.

00:06:35.190 --> 00:06:39.210 align:middle line:84%
It's like, oh my god, it's not
until I become something other

00:06:39.210 --> 00:06:42.420 align:middle line:84%
than a woman that I have
credibility and validity.

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:45.290 align:middle line:84%
I have to be a TV editor,
or a newspaper reporter,

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:47.830 align:middle line:84%
or a teacher, or
something like that.

00:06:47.830 --> 00:06:49.210 align:middle line:90%
Then I have credibility.

00:06:49.210 --> 00:06:49.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:50.810 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:53.880 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now let's go
and do the back story,

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:58.830 align:middle line:84%
because you were raised in late
'50s, early '60s, a little girl

00:06:58.830 --> 00:07:03.070 align:middle line:84%
in America with a mother
who played the classic role,

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:09.260 align:middle line:84%
and a stepfather who played a
maybe less than classic role,

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:11.910 align:middle line:84%
but certainly not a very
positive one in your life.

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:15.897 align:middle line:84%
So let's go back
to the beginning.

00:07:15.897 --> 00:07:18.480 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: Yeah, and I used to
think that "Father Knows Best,"

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:21.310 align:middle line:84%
because that was the kind
of television programming

00:07:21.310 --> 00:07:22.760 align:middle line:90%
I was raised with.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:26.910 align:middle line:84%
I looked at my family
dynamics, which were sorely

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:29.260 align:middle line:84%
dysfunctional in comparison
to "Father Knows Best,"

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:33.140 align:middle line:84%
and I wondered,
well, what's wrong?

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:37.580 align:middle line:84%
What's wrong with me that I
didn't get that kind of family.

00:07:37.580 --> 00:07:40.400 align:middle line:84%
My mom was a tomboy
who learned not

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:45.770 align:middle line:84%
to be a tomboy, who learned
to be more submissive,

00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:49.930 align:middle line:84%
be polite, never say anything
against what a man would say,

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:53.552 align:middle line:84%
and she suppressed
all of her joie de

00:07:53.552 --> 00:07:56.540 align:middle line:84%
vivre to mold herself
in a direction

00:07:56.540 --> 00:07:59.860 align:middle line:84%
that her society and that
her family had indicated

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:00.830 align:middle line:90%
was the way to go.

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:04.360 align:middle line:84%
And she tried her
best to get me to go

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:07.840 align:middle line:84%
in that direction, all the
while kind of under the table

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:12.510 align:middle line:84%
not wanting me to subdue my
own tomboy tendencies at all.

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:15.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It was a fine line
for her to walk in raising you.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:16.051 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: It really was.

00:08:16.051 --> 00:08:18.740 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And because your
stepfather was an angry man.

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:20.740 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: He was an
angry, wounded man,

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:25.130 align:middle line:84%
and it's easy to say he did
the best he could considering.

00:08:25.130 --> 00:08:25.986 align:middle line:90%
But he was--

00:08:25.986 --> 00:08:27.110 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: He did a bad job.

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:28.930 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: He did a
very, very bad job.

00:08:28.930 --> 00:08:33.159 align:middle line:84%
And very violent, abusive,
fortunately not physically

00:08:33.159 --> 00:08:36.390 align:middle line:84%
and sexually, but of course
then the emotional abuse,

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:39.320 align:middle line:84%
and the verbal abuse is actually
sometimes even more subtle.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.280 align:middle line:84%
At least if you've had
your head knocked off,

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:44.690 align:middle line:84%
it's kind of like
therapeutic and purgative.

00:08:44.690 --> 00:08:46.020 align:middle line:90%
It's just like, oh, OK.

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:49.090 align:middle line:84%
But the rest is just
more subtly undermining.

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:51.742 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The death by 1,000
cuts, I think it's called.

00:08:51.742 --> 00:08:53.430 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: There you go.

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:55.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so your
mother was essentially

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:58.100 align:middle line:84%
the walking wounded for
a big part of her life.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:00.240 align:middle line:84%
>>MONTANA: And the
peacemaker no matter what,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:04.490 align:middle line:84%
because my step dad and I
would just go toe to toe.

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:07.500 align:middle line:84%
So she would always
intervene, and smooth, put oil

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:08.270 align:middle line:90%
on the waters.

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:13.080 align:middle line:84%
And so she played a very
classic feminine role.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:18.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But she also played
a role that was beyond not

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:22.260 align:middle line:84%
supportive of you at a time when
you experienced a molestation

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:23.612 align:middle line:90%
by the neighborhood paperboy.

00:09:23.612 --> 00:09:24.320 align:middle line:90%
>>MONTANA: Right.

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:27.285 align:middle line:84%
